</ol>

<p>The tool works for both <strong>.yaml</strong> and <strong>.yml</strong> files — they are the same format, just different extensions.</p>

<h2>YAML vs JSON — Key Differences</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Comments:</strong> YAML supports comments (<code># this is a comment</code>). JSON does not. Comments are dropped during conversion.</li>
  <li><strong>Syntax:</strong> YAML uses indentation for structure; JSON uses curly braces and brackets.</li>
  <li><strong>Data types:</strong> YAML infers types (integers, booleans, nulls) from unquoted values. JSON always requires explicit quoting for strings.</li>
  <li><strong>Readability:</strong> YAML is more human-readable; JSON is more explicit and widely supported by tools.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Common YAML to JSON Use Cases</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Kubernetes:</strong> Convert deployment.yaml to JSON for <code>kubectl</code> API calls or custom tooling.</li>
  <li><strong>GitHub Actions:</strong> Parse workflow YAML as JSON for analysis or automation.</li>
  <li><strong>Docker Compose:</strong> Convert docker-compose.yml to JSON for programmatic processing.</li>
  <li><strong>OpenAPI / Swagger:</strong> Convert OpenAPI YAML specs to JSON for tools that require JSON format.</li>
  <li><strong>Helm charts:</strong> Transform values.yaml to JSON for debugging or templating.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What About YML to JSON?</h2>

<p>
  <strong>.yml</strong> is just a shorter version of the <strong>.yaml</strong> file extension — both use the identical YAML format. The same <a href="/data/yaml-to-json">YAML to JSON converter</a> handles both. There is no difference in how the files are parsed.
</p>

<p>
